  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen firsthand in my own life as a woman working in an electrician's trade. Growing up in Bari, my parents' different educational backgrounds taught me early that success isn't about how much you know but how you apply it. My father, who has a vocational diploma, showed me the value of hands-on work, while my mother, with a bachelor's degree, helped me see the importance of understanding the 'why' behind things. This balance has shaped my approach to my job, where I often find myself explaining complex electrical systems to clients in simple terms, just like my dad taught me. Stereotype threat happens when people feel their identity is at risk because of societal expectations—like when a woman in STEM feels she must prove herself to be taken seriously. In my part-time work, I've noticed that some clients assume I won't understand technical jargon because I'm a woman, which makes me nervous before even starting a task. But I've learned that addressing this isn't about changing people's minds—it's about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of judgment. In my community, especially in Bari where many people are close-knit, we can start small: encouraging women to join workshops without pressure, celebrating small wins, and making sure everyone knows their skills matter. I believe addressing stereotype threat requires empathy, not just data. It's about recognizing that when someone feels their worth is tied to a group label, they can't focus on the work at hand. As a mother of two, I know that building confidence in my children is about creating environments where they feel they belong. So yes, we must address stereotype threat in STEM—it's not just about fixing the system but about nurturing the people who build it.",
